<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12238&amp;p=140665#p140665"><![CDATA[
Hey...seeing all these explosions got me thinking...what if you tried to create a radially-symmetric explosion? You would have to go for a very stylized look, but you could create a 64x64 explosion by only drawing the 32x32 parts of the explosion. Here's a really rough example of what I'm talking about...Ideally the final explosion would be seamless along the boundaries and use a lot more colors.<br /><br /><img src="http://fc04.deviantart.net/fs71/f/2015/036/5/b/snes_explosion_by_dragondeplatino-d8gt9z3.gif" alt="Image" /><br />(6 frames of 32x32 sprites)<br /><br />Oh! Or you could go for a really stylized circle-style explosion like I did for my <a href="http://www.spriters-resource.com/custom_edited/digdug/sheet/63718/" class="postlink">Dig Dug NES sheet</a>:<br /><br /><img src="http://fc09.deviantart.net/fs71/f/2015/036/f/f/nes_explosion_tiles_by_dragondeplatino-d8gt9z1.png" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://fc04.deviantart.net/fs70/f/2015/036/e/7/nes_explosion_by_dragondeplatino-d8gt9yu.gif" alt="Image" /><br /><img src="http://fc03.deviantart.net/fs70/f/2015/036/8/2/nes_explosion_frames_by_dragondeplatino-d8gt9yw.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />The whole thing only uses 8 minisprites, but it takes up a 64x64 space and creates no sprite flickering by itself. Frames 9-16 are 8 overlapping minisprites across at their widest points.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6734">DragonDePlatino</a> — Thu Feb 05, 2015 4:04 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
